  The 10 Advanced Nuances Your Mandate Misses

  1. Supervisor Self-Healing Paradox: If JarvisSystemKernel crashes, nothing restores it. Your mandate mentions this but has no solution. You need a minimal
  bootstrap watchdog OUTSIDE the supervisor (launchd on macOS, systemd on Linux).
  2. Hot-Swap Coherence Gap: Prime can hot-swap models (zero-downtime), but JARVIS's routing table doesn't learn about swaps in real-time. There's a
  stale-routing window where JARVIS routes to a model that Prime just unloaded.
  3. Memory Pressure Cascade: JARVIS monitors memory and can trigger GCP offload. But if both JARVIS (monitoring) and Prime (inference) are on the same 16GB
  Mac, the act of monitoring consumes memory that could be used for inference. The observer affects the observed.
  4. Event Ordering Under Partition: If the WebSocket between JARVIS and Prime drops, events queue locally. When reconnected, events replay. But if Prime
  processed some events via the Reactor Bridge during the partition, you get duplicate execution or ordering violations.
  5. Deadline Propagation Across Repos: Your mandate mentions deadline propagation within JARVIS, but deadlines don't cross repo boundaries. A 30s request to
   JARVIS that calls Prime (which calls Reactor) has no end-to-end timeout budget.
  6. Clock Skew Between Repos: JARVIS uses time.monotonic() (correctly!), but health check timestamps between repos use datetime.now(). If repos run on
  different machines (local Mac + GCP VM), clock skew can make health checks appear stale when they're actually fresh.
  7. Singleton Registry Fragmentation: Each repo has its own singleton pattern. JARVIS uses get_gcp_vm_manager(), Prime uses its own factories, Reactor uses
  its own. There's no cross-repo singleton awareness — you could theoretically have two VM managers if both repos instantiate one.
  8. Graceful Degradation vs. Crash Consistency: Your system degrades gracefully (falling back tiers), but it doesn't guarantee crash consistency. If JARVIS
  crashes mid-way through writing a cloud lock file AND updating the event store, which one wins on restart?
  9. The 75 Design Docs Problem: 72 design documents since January 2026. That's roughly one per day. This suggests a pattern of planning-without-convergence
  — each design addresses a specific symptom but the unified architecture never stabilizes because the foundation (Disease 1-3) keeps shifting.
  10. No Formal Ownership Boundaries: Your mandate beautifully defines ownership (Body/Mind/Nerves), but the code doesn't enforce it. There's no __init__.py
  that controls what Prime exposes to JARVIS. Any file can import any other file across repos by manipulating sys.path.

